@MiaD Pan instructions (1):
Heat 1 tablespoon of olive oil in a large pot like a Dutch oven
Dice the onion in 1 tablespoon of olive oil and fry until translucent and beginning to caramelize.
Add all the diced peppers and fry them until they soften.

@MiaD Ingredients(4 & last)
1 tablespoon ancho chili powder
2 teaspoons ground cumin
2 teaspoons garlic powder
2 tablespoons smoked peppers
1 tablespoon Montreal Steak Seasoning
Salt and pepper to taste

@MiaD Ingredients(3)
2-3 rehydrated dried ancho chilies
1 large onion - diced
1 yellow, orange or red and green bell pepper - diced
6 cups of cooked beans. I like kidney, navy, pinto and black. (About 4 cans)
1 12 oz. lager
2 tablespoons olive oil
1 TBSP Chili Power

@MiaD Ingredients(2)
1-2 tablespoons of Adobo sauce

@roxanasoi @butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 Totally agree with you Roxana. Of course I do. These are problems of flawless logic. Since these types of vaccines are based on the immune defenses, any problems in the immune defenses obviously lead to problems in the effectiveness of these vaccines...
@butera_simone Yes, in the same boat Simone ! https://t.co/XzXe3OP0WX

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 15/ To conclude, for me the problem which can be troublesome is the possibility of extreme reactions of our immune defenses (but can't happen on the older people) that could lead to complications in some people (such as allergies ... and I am allergic ...).
Hope it helps Simone.

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 14/ So It makes sense to think that current vaccines will work well with mutants of the virus (because only few of the amino acids on the spike protein will be modified).

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 13/ but this is not going to lead to a change in the function of the protein (the surface protein for example, the Spike protein, that has around 1300 amino acids).

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 12/ We must also know that RNA viruses (as the sars-cov2) mutate much more easily and quickly than DNA viruses. Why is this? Because at each replication, nucleic acids are poorly copied with errors. And mutant viruses appear as we can see now.

@roxanasoi @butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 10/ & the cells producing the Spike protein following the injection of the vaccine are rapidly destroyed by the immune system. The foreign RNA doesn't stay in the body for long & is there to train the immune system to respond to an infection with the virus before it's eliminated.

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 9/ as the Spike protein produced by the organism is extremely close to its natural conformation in the wild virus. 
+ The RNA injected has no risk of transforming our genome since it does not penetrate the nucleus of the cells, where our genetic material is located.

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 8/ Other advantages can be raised. These include the triggering of a powerful and very specific immune response to the virus. This strategy is characterized by the production of highly neutralizing antibodies and T lymphocytes specific to the viral antigen,

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 6/ Furthermore, the fact that these vaccines are not based on whole viruses and do not use adjuvants in their development, but simply nucleic acid molecules, also means that they are better tolerated by the body.

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 5/ With RNA vaccines, much of the development and manufacturing process for traditional vaccines is eliminated, and RNA molecules are simpler than viral proteins: they are enzymatically synthesized and faster to produce.

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 4/ However, it is only recently that solutions have been found. And so Pfizer/BioNTech & Moderna use nanolipid particles to transport the vaccine RNA to the cells.

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 3/ RNA molecules are 10 times larger than an antigen in protein form directly injected via a traditional vaccine.

 Scientists therefore had to develop a system for transporting these molecules to the right place within the cells of interest.

@butera_simone @giacomozucco @peterktodd @NickSzabo4 2/ Researchers have been working on these types of techs for several decades. However, they faced technical obstacles and especially the size of RNA molecules in particular that was problematic. That's what explains why this vaccine tech hasn't been used until recently.
